{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"When a required key is absent from both the file and the environment, the error message names the missing key by its exact config path (e.g., `database.host`).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff across local modules: file config load + environment override merge + required-key validation + error formatting. The behavior text explicitly requires absence in two sources (\"both the file and the environment\"), so a single-function check is too narrow. Higher levels are disqualified because no real OS/network/subprocess behavior is required and there is no AI/ML output dependency.","test_description":"Run the real config-loading stack with a config missing `database.host` and no corresponding `TOOL_` env var set; assert startup fails and the emitted message contains the exact path `database.host`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the environment variable `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` is set, the loader resolves the config file path relative to that directory rather than `~/.config`.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is path-resolution logic for one boundary (inputs: env vars, home path; output: resolved config path). Concrete behavior text does not require filesystem creation, subprocesses, or network. Higher levels are disqualified because the check can be reproduced with fixed inputs to a local resolver function.","test_description":"Call the path resolver with `XDG_CONFIG_HOME=/tmp/xdg` (and a known home path) and assert the resulting config path is `/tmp/xdg/tool/config.yaml`, not `~/.config/tool/config.yaml`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When an environment variable with the `TOOL_` prefix conflicts with a key in the config file, the environment variable value is used.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure appears at module boundaries: YAML/file-sourced value and env-sourced override must be normalized to the same key path, then precedence applied correctly. A unit test of only merge logic can miss mapping/wiring defects between loaders. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text: no real OS/network/subprocess dependency and no AI/ML-dependent correctness.","test_description":"Load config through the normal loader path with file value set for a key and conflicting `TOOL_` env var set; assert effective runtime config uses the env value.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the config file contains a YAML syntax error, the error message includes the line number where the problem was detected.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Catching this requires real interaction with the YAML parser module plus loader error translation. Mocking parser errors can hide real exception-shape/line-number propagation bugs. System was considered but disqualified by behavior text: this is parser+loader interaction, not OS/network/subprocess behavior.","test_description":"Provide malformed YAML to the real loader/parser path and assert the emitted error includes a line number corresponding to the parser-detected syntax error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the config directory does not exist at startup, the loader creates it and writes a defaults file before proceeding.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on real filesystem primitives at startup (existence check